					<msContents class="lccn.loc.gov/sh85070287" rend="visible">
						<summary>Sefer ha-ḥinukh, a commentary on the 613 precepts arranged in the order of the weekly parashiyot.</summary>
						<textLang mainLang="he">Hebrew</textLang>
						<msItem rend="visible" class="lccn.loc.gov/sh85070287">
							<locus from="1r" to="289v"/>
							<title xml:lang="en">Sefer ha-ḥinukh</title>
							<title xml:lang="he">ספר החינוך</title>
							<note>
								<p>The attribution to Aaron of Barcelona is not certain. </p>
								<p>The various quotations from Maimonides' Sefer mitsṿot are taken from Avraham ben Ḥasdai's Hebrew translation of that work. </p>
								<p>The manuscript differs slightly from the printed editions.</p>
							</note>
							<author key="http://viaf.org/viaf/86224841">
								<persName key="http://viaf.org/viaf/86224841" xml:lang="en">Aaron, ha-Levi, of Barcelona, active 13th century-14th century</persName>
								<persName key="http://viaf.org/viaf/86224841" xml:lang="he">אהרן, הלוי, מברצלונה </persName>
							</author>
							<listBibl>
								<bibl>
									<ref target="Sefer_hahinukh_1721"/>
								</bibl>
							</listBibl>
							<colophon xml:lang="he">בפניי אליהו הנבי"א בכמה"ר יהודה וצבי הרופא נבתוי"א הכ"מ קבל מ"ר שמואל הרופא מאגוביאו בכ"ר יואב ז"ל זה החנוך מכמ"ר מרדכי מעירנו ושלחהו לו ע"י אנטוניאו חמר[?] ב' באלול <date when="1373" calendar="Hebrew">שקל"ג</date> והם י"ד קונטריסים כתובי' וי"ד קונטריסי' חלק'  והיה זה שלו' שהם בין הכל שמנה ועשרים".<locus n="2r"/>
							</colophon>
						</msItem>
					</msContents>
					<physDesc rend="visible">
						<p>Parchment codex of the 14th century.</p>
						<objectDesc form="codex">
							<supportDesc material="perg">
								<extent>290 folios <dimensions unit="mm" type="leaf">
										<height>275</height>
										<width>190</width>
									</dimensions>
									<dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
										<height>190</height>
										<width>125</width>
									</dimensions>
								</extent>
								<foliation>
									<p>290 folios (+ 2 modern paper flyleaves at the beginning and at the end). Folios 1 and 290 are vellum flyleaves.</p>
								</foliation>
								<collation>
									<p>30 quires of mostly 10 leaves each, marked with catchwords  and Hebrew letters at the end.</p>
									<p>Quires no. 12, 21, 22, 25 have 8 leaves each, quire no. 30 has 6 leaves only.</p>
								</collation>
								<condition>
									<p>Folio 290 is only partly preserved.</p>
								</condition>
							</supportDesc>
							<layoutDesc>
								<layout columns="1 " ruledLines="34" writtenLines="34">
									<p>Uniform layout. Visible pricking and hard-point ruling (bifolium by bifolium).</p>
									<p>Hair-side and flesh-side of the folios distinguishable, with visible scratching.</p>
									<p>Last line written outside the ruling.</p>
									<p>Occasional infralinear vocalization.</p>
									<p>Chapter numbers in the margins, within pen and ink simple design.</p>
								</layout>
							</layoutDesc>
						</objectDesc>
						<handDesc hands="3">
							<summary>Italian semi-cursive script of the 14th century. Avraham (?), the scribe: his name marked off within the text.</summary>
							<handNote script="Hebrew" scope="sole">
								<p>
									<locus from="3r" to="96v"/>, <locus from="100v" to="109r"/>and <locus from="208r" to="229r"/> due to the 1st hand (i.e. Avraham); <locus from="109v" to="207v"/> and <locus from="230r" to="289v"/> due to the 2nd hand; <locus from="97r" to="100v"/>, <locus from="229v" to="230r"/> due to the 3rd hand.</p>
							</handNote>
						</handDesc>
